always in reactive programming a fxn is expected to return result of Mono





first step
- in yaml set all the path predicates and routing
eg -
    spring:
      cloud:
        gateway:
          server:
            webflux:
              routes:
                - id: route1
                  uri: https://google.com
                  predicates:
                    - Path=/api/first/**

                - id: route2
                  uri: https://facebook.com
                  predicates:
                    - Path=/api/second/**



then use actuator as
/actuator/health — is the app up (the one everyone knows)
/actuator/metrics — request counts, JVM memory, GC pauses, custom counters you define
/actuator/env — what config properties actually got loaded (great for "why isn't my YAML value being picked up" debugging)
/actuator/beans — every Spring bean in the context
/actuator/gateway/routes — Gateway-specific: literally dumps the in-memory route list Spring Cloud Gateway built from your YAML

with the help of management add req things as endpoint req

so actuator is used in like managing it use id
but for actual route we have to use uri


API throttling - number of request a user can make in a given amount of time

rate limit                                  api throttling
limit reach reject                          limit = slow
send status 429                             slow the speed after exhaust of limit


in filter we need to add the rate limiter if using spring rate limiter then provide argument for that under args:
as

routes:
  - id: route1
    uri: http://localhost:9000
    predicates:
      - Path=/api/first/**
    filters:
      - name: RequestRateLimiter
        args:
          redis-rate-limiter.replenishRate: 10
          redis-rate-limiter.burstCapacity: 20
          redis-rate-limiter.requestedTokens: 1
          key-resolver: "#{@userKeyResolver}"

args: map to fields on that filter's Config class:

replenishRate — tokens added per second (steady-state allowed rate)
burstCapacity — max bucket size (how much burst above steady rate is tolerated)
requestedTokens — how many tokens this request consumes (usually 1, could be more for expensive endpoints)

key-resolver — this is the part that decides who gets rate-limited as a unit — per-user, per-IP, per-API-key. It references a Spring bean via SpEL (#{@beanName}), which you must define yourself:


key-resolver is used as key for rate limiter like id of device or something
interface deciding where this request is coming from
in webmvc we use http-request-servlet but in
webflux :
exchange.getRequest().getHeaders().getFirst("")

and one key-resolver bean is req as it needs some key
@Bean
public KeyResolver userKeyResolver() {
    return exchange -> Mono.just(
        exchange.getRequest().getHeaders().getFirst("X-User-Id")
    );
}